      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm working on a collision system for a game and i need to get some AABB tree stuff running. i need a class that can take a list of bounding boxes and return which ones are actually overlapping. \n\nthe performance needs to be decent because we're gonna have a lot of objects, so a simple nested loop won't cut it for the final build. \n\nhere are the test cases i'm using to verify the logic. can u implement the tree and make sure it passes these?\n\n```python\ndef test_collisions():\n    # Box format: (id, min_x, min_y, min_z, max_x, max_y, max_z)\n    boxes = [\n        (0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1),\n        (1, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 1.5, 1.5, 1.5),\n        (2, 10, 10, 10, 11, 11, 11),\n        (3, 0.2, 0.2, 0.2, 0.8, 0.8, 0.8),\n        (4, 5, 5, 5, 6, 6, 6)\n    ]\n    \n    tree = AABBTree(boxes)\n    collisions = tree.get_collision_pairs()\n    \n    # Expected pairs (as sets of IDs to ignore order)\n    # 0 intersects 1\n    # 0 intersects 3\n    # 1 intersects 3\n    # 2 and 4 do not intersect anything\n    expected = [{\"0\", \"1\"}, {\"0\", \"3\"}, {\"1\", \"3\"}]\n    \n    # Convert results to sets of strings for comparison\n    actual = [set(map(str, pair)) for pair in collisions]\n    \n    assert len(actual) == len(expected), f\"Expected {len(expected)} pairs, got {len(actual)}\"\n    for pair in expected:\n        assert pair in actual, f\"Missing pair: {pair}\"\n\n# Run the test\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    test_collisions()\n    print(\"Tests passed!\")\n```",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The AABB (Axis-Aligned Bounding Box) tree is a spatial partitioning data structure particularly well-suited for efficiently finding potential collisions in a large number of objects. It works by recursively dividing the space into smaller regions (and therefore smaller AABBs) until each region either contains enough objects to be checked in detail for their bounding boxes directly or it is sufficiently small such that the objects contained within it can be considered to have possibly collided (i.e., they share edges or corners).\n\nAs for the provided tests, the expected pairs ${ \"0\", \"1\" }, { \"0\", \"3\" }, { \"1\", \"3\" } $ confirm that when constructing the AABB tree with the provided boxes, objects 0, 1, and 3 do collide with each other because their bounding boxes overlap. None of the other objects, 2 or 4, have overlapping bounding boxes with anyone else, reflected by the fact that we don't find them in the output of the `get_collision_pairs()` method when those pairs are not mentioned, or that they do not intersect with each other.\n\nThe algorithms used to determine collisions and construct the AABB tree itself generally ensures that the number of checks scales well with the number of objects",
      "source": "target",
